<HEAD>Philippines Vice President Urges Marcos Return to Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with Laurel back in Manila, quoting
doctors saying Marcos has lost will to live. Pick up 3rd pvs, `The Philippine...'
Edits thereafter to trim and conform.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> said Saturday that doctors fear <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> has lost the will to live, has only a 10 percent chance of surviving the year, and wants to die in his own country. Laurel spoke to reporters after returning from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, where the ousted <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> president, accused of plundering billions from his homeland, is in exile. He said he would seek a meeting immediately with President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to relay <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' wish and appeal `` to her sense of Christian values'' to allow the former president to come home to die. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has refused to allow <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> or members of his family to return from <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, where they have lived since a popular uprising toppled his 20-year administration in February 1986. <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> said doctors in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> told him that <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> might not survive the trip to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> but that the former president would prefer to die on the plane rather than on foreign soil. A newspaper in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> quoted a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> official as saying Saturday that the government has decided not to allow <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return and would even bar his body from being sent back after he dies. The Philippine Daily Inquirer quoted Cabinet Secretary <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> as saying the government feared <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' supporters would try to destabilize the <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> administration if their leader came home. `` We ca n't risk the gains by any destabilization effort which could derail us,'' <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> was quoted as saying. The newspaper quoted unidentified government sources as saying the Cabinet considered allowing <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return to <LOCATION> Laoag </LOCATION>, capital of his home province of <ORGANIZATION> Ilocos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Norte </ORGANIZATION> about 250 miles north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. But the idea was rejected because of fears <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> would not honor the restriction, the paper Laurel visited <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' hospital bedside Thursday without Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s blessing. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, 71, remained in critical condition Friday in <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>'s intensive care unit, but an attorney said <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was buoyed by <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION>'s visit and doctors said his fever had subsided. <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> declined to disclose details of his conversations with <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, his doctors and his wife, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>. `` Whatever our past differences and conflicts, the reality is that the crisis in this man's life can seriously affect political stability of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Now is the time for compassion and forgiveness in order to achieve much needed unity among all Filipinos,'' <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> said in a statement Thursday night. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his wife are under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> indictment for allegedly plundering the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> of more than $ 100 million and stashing much of the money in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. When <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION> was asked whether <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> would ever return to his homeland, he replied: `` That's up to her,'' referring to Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' son, <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said he relayed a letter to Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> asking that his father be allowed to return. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, who has repeatedly refused to allow <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return, said she had not received the letter. `` I can just make a decision once I know what the letter is all about,'' she told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> conceded his was a personal, not official, visit, but said he would make a full report to Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was breathing with the assistance of a respirator following emergency surgery Wednesday to reduce fluids building up in his lungs. Hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Kop </PERSON> said <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was alert but unable to talk because of the respirator. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was admitted to the hospital Jan. 15 for treatment of pneumonia and bronchial asthma. In December, he was hospitalized twice with congestive heart failure. The Marcoses would need permission from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney general and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to leave the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> LaBella </PERSON>, the prosecutor in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government's racketeering case against <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his wife. A federal judge in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> is to decide this month whether <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> is healthy enough to stand trial on criminal racketeering charges. Mrs. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> pleaded innocent and is free on $ 5 million bail.
