<HEAD>Doctor, Clothing Chain Founders Charged With Murder In Insurance
Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The owner of the Just Sweats clothing chain, his partner and a doctor were charged with murder Friday in an alleged $ 1.5 million insurance scam involving the faked death of the owner. <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, co-founder of the <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, Ohio-based athletic clothing chain; his partner, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>; and Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryde </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Glendale </LOCATION> were charged in the murder of <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, 32. <PERSON> Green </PERSON>'s body was found in <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON>' office April 16 and was misidentified as that of <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, 47, who was arrested last week carrying <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>'s driver's license, is being held in a <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, jail on grand theft charges under a $ 5 million bond <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, 25, who collected $ 1 million in death benefits on <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, remains at large. <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON>, 56, was arrested Friday and held without bail pending arraignment Monday. <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> was believed dead until mid-1988, when police in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> discovered that a man identified as <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> who died in <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON>' office was not <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>. The discovery and the fact that <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> had cashed $ 1 million in life insurance checks prompted authorities to file federal warrants for their arrest. Authorities allege that <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>'s death was faked to collect the insurance money. The murder charges against all three men carry special circumstances that make them eligible for the death penalty. The special circumstances alleged are murder for financial gain and aiding and abetting. Ten charges were filed against each man, including murder, conspiracy to commit murder, insurance fraud, grand theft, and assault with a stun gun. <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON>, 56, told police he believed the man found dead in his office was <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>. He said the man died after complaining of chest pains. <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> had the body cremated the next day. Police later discovered that a thumbprint from the corpse did not match the one on <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> driver's license. The body, which resembled <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>, later was identified as <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, a former Ohioan who lived in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> also are accused of stealing about $ 2 million from Just Sweats, which they founded in 1985. The company has filed for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bankruptcy code.
