<HEAD>Critics Say Consult Arrangement Promotes Conflict of Interest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> wanted to prepare an annual report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on its Superfund toxic waste cleanup program, it sought out a consultant. <ORGANIZATION> ICF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> prepared the document for $ 260,000. Congressional critics maintain that little more than the letterhead was changed on the draft received from the private company before it was sent to <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` Three words were changed, two ` ands' and a ` the','' complained Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, D-Ark., who held a hearing Friday on the widespread use of private consultants by the federal agency responsible for cleaning up the environment He said one of his major concerns is that many of the consultants working for the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> `` also have private sector clients from the very industries the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> is charged with regulating'' raising questions about conflict of interest. <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> and other critics suggested that the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> _ and most likely other federal agencies and departments as well _ are relying too heavily on private contractors to do work, including critical analysis and often decision-making, that the government ought to be doing. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials acknowledged in testimony before <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>'s Government Affairs subcommittee that they make extensive use of consultants, but maintained that precautions are taken to avoid a conflict of interest. They insisted that decision-making remains in agency hands. `` It comes down to workload. It's a matter of resources,'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Longest </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s Superfund cleanup program, where contractors are used widely, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel. But <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, who has waged a decade-long fight against the federal government's extensive use of private consultants, did not accept the explanation. `` Consultants do everything from working on enforcing compliance with <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> regulations to writing <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s annual reports,'' Pryor declared in opening the hearing. `` It appears that the basic work of <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has been delegated to private consultants.'' The senator cited the case of a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> subcontractor found by congressional investigators to have recommended a particular cleanup method for a toxic waste dump. It turned out that the same company owned the rights for that cleanup method and was given the job, said <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>. <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> also cited the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> contracts with <ORGANIZATION> ICF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, including the one for preparing the agency's annual report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Superfund, as another example where questions of conflict of interest might be raised. While <ORGANIZATION> ICF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has several so-called `` sliding'' contracts with the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> valued for as much as $ 15 million, it also aggressively seeks business with private companies that are subject to <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> regulation and `` boasts of its <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> connection in its promotional literature,'' said <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>. Earlier this week the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION>, which is <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' scientific research agency, also criticized the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> for relying too much on contractors in its Superfund cleanup program, suggesting that contractors and not <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials are running the program. Superfund is the $ 8.5 billion program through which the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> is tackling hundreds of toxic waste cleanup projects across the country.
