<HEAD>Shortage of Disposable Syringes Delays Oregon AIDS Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A program to help prevent the spread of AIDS among intravenous drug abusers by distributing free sterile needles has been delayed due to a shortage of disposable syringes, organizers said. The sponsoring agencies, Portland-based Outside In and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for AIDS Research, had planned for the program to begin in July but had difficulty insuring the program. The groups found a company in November to provide medical liability insurance, but <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> stipulated that the distributed needles must be of such a design that they could not be re-used. Outside In has been negotiating with a British company to supply single-use hypodermic syringes, agency director <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> said Wednesday. Delivery had been promised Jan. 1, but the manufacturer ca n't mass produce them, she said. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> said the supplier is having 1,500 syringes manufactured each month. Outside In will need a couple of thousand each month for its distribution program, she said. She said she did n't know when the supply problem would be resolved. Epidemiologists have said that direct blood contamination through shared needles is the most rapid way acquired immune deficiency syndrome is being spread.
