<SECOND>PM-Antarctic Spill,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seals, Penguins Harmed By Oil Spill In Antarctic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUNTA ARENAS, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A ship laden with more than 50 tons of equipment headed toward the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> today to try and contain an oil spill that experts say is killing wildlife and threatening to wipe out a colony of baby penguins. The spill, from a sunken Argentine supply ship, has fouled the once-pure waters of a pristine bay and was endangering more than 24,000 penguins and other nesting birds, said biologist <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laca </PERSON>. `` It's very disturbing. Everything right now is worrisome,'' said <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laca </PERSON>, a researcher at the Palmer Station, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> research outpost on the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. About 52 tons of equipment flown from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was loaded onto the 219-foot Polar <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> here from a giant <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> C-5 Galaxy cargo plane. The Polar Duke departed shortly after 6 p.m. Friday and was expected to reach the area in four days. The oil is leaking from the Argentine research and supply ship <ORGANIZATION> Bahia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paraiso </ORGANIZATION>, which is trapped and nearly submerged on shoals in the <LOCATION> Bismarck </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> just off the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> peninsula. Thousands of penguins, terns, gulls and other birds live around the site of the accident, and the waters teem with marine life, including whales. Two areas nearby are set aside by the Antarctic Treaty for scientific study. Punta Arenas is at the windblown tip of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> about 600 miles from the stricken Argentine vessel. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Forhan </PERSON>, ocean projects manager for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, leads the cleanup mission. American scientists, wearing respirators as protection against the smell of oil fumes, are working in open boats to try to limit the damage, but <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laca </PERSON> said `` virtually all of the area is exposed to fuel,'' causing young birds to disappear and killing small sea animals `` in large numbers.'' De <PERSON> Laca </PERSON> spoke by telephone with the The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. About 24,000 penguins nest in rookeries in the affected area, and <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laca </PERSON> said 38 of the 40 adult birds checked by scientists have been `` fuel-dipped.'' The fear of the experts, he said, is that penguin chicks, due to leave nests within a few days, will swim in the oil-coated water and be sickened or killed. At least three dead penguins have been sighted, said <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laca </PERSON>. `` All of the rookeries are surrounded by oil,'' he said. A number of seals were seen to be covered with oil and were acting in a `` lethargic fashion,'' said the scientist. `` We have a slick 150 meters -LRB- yards -RRB- by 2 miles long going south from the vessel,'' moving `` along and a little bit away'' from the coast, <PERSON> Forhan </PERSON> said in an interview aboard the Polar Duke. He said there were reports of birds smothered by oil and of dead krill, shrimp-like creatures that whales feed upon in large numbers, floating ashore. Scientists and workers at <LOCATION> Palmer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> collected 112 compressed gas cylinders and 15 oil drums from the waters around the wreck, <PERSON> Forhan </PERSON> said, and `` there are more in the water.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Bahia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paraiso </ORGANIZATION> ran aground Jan. 25. The more than 250 people aboard were taken off without injury. Authorities said the ship carried at least 200,000 gallons of fuel oil in its tanks and more in drums lashed to the deck.
</TEXT>
