<HEAD>Bush Promises to Work on Opening Japanese Markets</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says U.S.-Japanese relations entail `` some confrontation at times'' and vows to make sure that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businesses gain fair access to markets in that nation. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spoke Friday at a White House luncheon for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business leaders as Japanese Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> wrapped up a two-day visit to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> was leaving Friday night for <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and a meeting there next week with former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Speaking of the barriers <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies face entering Japanese markets, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> pledged `` to do my level best ... to be sure that we are treated fairly, that we have access, that we ... are not operating under standards that favor one side to the detriment of the other.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> observed that he and <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> `` are realistic men ... and we realize we are going to have some confrontation at times, or certainly differences of opinion.'' The president added that he believes the prime minister `` wants very much to have a cooperative relationship.'' On Thursday, the two men pledged after their 2 -LCB- - hour meeting and lunch to strive to smooth irritations over the $ 50 billion <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and tensions over the Japanese contributions to its defense effort <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not elaborate on the details of the trade problems he and the prime minister discussed on Thursday, but said they'd `` reviewed the progress that our nations have achieved in bringing the economies into better balance and of further opening our markets to each other's goods and services. He added that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> carries `` a disproportionate responsibility for the defense requirements of free countries'' and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, `` given its economic standing today, is willing to accept much more in the way of responsibility for helping ... in the whole development aid side of things.'' `` I just wanted to assure you that the visit yesterday had gone reasonably well,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the businessmen. As the president spoke, Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> bid <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> a formal farewell at the end of his two-day <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> visit with a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> luncheon of champagne toasts, pheasant and ice cream with mangoes. In remarks at the luncheon, the secretary of state also struck a cautionary note, telling <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> the two economic superpowers `` still face a difficult agenda.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> also expressed hope the partnership will grow stronger as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> assumes a broader world role. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is determined to do its utmost to collaborate with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, its strongest ally, for the peace and security of the world,'' the prime minister said, in his toast. `` No problems are unsolvable as long as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> join in an effort to solve them,'' <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> said.
