<FIRST>r w PM-AntarcticaShipwreck     02-04 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Antarctica Shipwreck,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Environmental Damage Grows From Antarctica Fuel Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Birds and other wildlife in one of the most remote parts of the world are being injured and killed by fuel oil spilled from a ship wrecked on an <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> island, and more damage is possible before cleanup crews arrive. Biologist <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laca </PERSON>, chief scientist at <ORGANIZATION> Palmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>, said that more than 24,000 penguins and other birds are endangered by an oil spill that threatens to wipe an entire generation of chicks maturing in nests surrounded by the pollution. Some wildlife already has been killed, he said. `` The environment has been compromised in a way that we ca n't even evaluate right now,'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laca </PERSON> said in a telephone conference call from <LOCATION> Palmer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> `` It's very disturbing. Everything right now is worrisome.'' Palmer Station scientists, wearing respirators to protect against the eye-stinging fumes of the oil slick, worked in open boats to recover debris littering the fouled bay and to evaluate the damage. But <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laca </PERSON> said a more effective effort to contain the spill must await the arrival Monday of a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> oil pollution control team from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He said the fuel oil is spilling from the Argentine ship <LOCATION> Bahia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paraiso </LOCATION> at the rate of about two gallons a minute and if it continues the vessel could dump about 250,000 gallons into the previously pure, untainted waters nearby. The ship, which doubled as a cruise ship and a supply vessel for an Argentine research station, ran aground near <LOCATION> Palmer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> last Saturday. It later floated free, went aground again 1.1 miles from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> outpost and then turned over on its right side against another island. As it turned, fuel oil and deck cargo spilled into the Palmer Station embayment, home to a number of large bird rookeries. Palmer Station is a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> research station. Twenty-six scientists and staff are now working at the station under the director of <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laca </PERSON>, the chief scientist. <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> is about 600 miles south of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Horn </LOCATION>, the tip of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laca </PERSON> reported that krill, a tiny shrimp-like crustacean, have been killed by the thousands and are lining the nearby beaches. Birds feeding on the krill seem sickened, he said. In a nesting area of the Polar Skua, a bird of prey, up to 40 percent of the chicks have disappeared, possibily because parent birds sickened by the oil are unable to protect their young, he said. About 24,000 penguins nest in rookies in the affected area, and <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laca </PERSON> said that 38 of 40 adult birds checked by scientists have been `` fuel dipped.'' A number of seals were seen to be covered with oil and were acting in a `` lethargic fashion,'' said the scientist. The precise number of animals killed by the oil is difficult to calculate because other animals quickly eat the dead. `` It's pretty depressing,'' he said.
</TEXT>
