<HEAD>Deaver Abandons Perjury Appeal, Cites Desire to Put it Behind Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former White House aide <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> says he is broke and tired of being `` a captive of the system.'' So, on Friday, he dropped the appeal of his conviction of lying to a congressional subcommittee and a federal grand jury, saying he wanted to `` put this period of my life behind me.'' <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON>, a top adviser to former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and a close friend of the former first family, said in a statement issued by his lawyers that he was dropping the appeal `` with the firm belief that I was not guilty of the charges of which I was convicted.'' However, he said, `` to proceed with this appeal means to continue to live in doubt, to continue to wait for a decision, and, if my appeal is successful, to face another trial, a process which could mean another two years of agony and doubt.'' He also said he could not continue the `` financial burden'' of the appeals process. The 50-year-old onetime <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> deputy chief of staff was fined $ 100,000 and ordered to perform 1,500 hours of community service for his three felony convictions in 1987 of lying about his lobbying of former administration colleagues after leaving the White House. `` My decision to withdraw my appeal does not come easily,'' <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> said in the statement issued as his lawyers asked the appellate court here to dismiss his appeal. `` It results from a number of factors, primarily my desire to put this period of my life behind me and get on with whatever lies ahead,'' <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> must now begin performing the community service which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Penfield </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> set as a condition of three years of probation when he sentenced him last September. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has not yet specified what type of community service he will order. <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> said his `` belief in my innocence has not changed from the day the long and arduous proceedings against me began three years ago.'' <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON> resigned as deputy White House chief of staff in 1985 to start a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> public relations firm. He was convicted in December 1987 of lying under oath to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> oversight and investigations subcommittee and a grand jury.
