<HEAD>Discovery Of Unexploded German Bomb Prompts Evacuation Of Thousands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 3,000 people were evacuated from the East End after a large unexploded German bomb dating from World War II was discovered at a housing site, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard reported. <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> bomb disposal officers called to the scene Friday worked through the night, but the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement it could take two days to render the 1,000-pound bomb harmless. The statement said the explosives would have to be steamed out of the bomb because it was considered too dangerous to try to transport the bomb from the area. The bomb was found standing upright against a wall in Whitechapel, haunt of the notorious murderer <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> the </PERSON> <PERSON> Ripper </PERSON>, who killed five women in 1888 and was never caught. It was unearthed by a mechanical digger driven by <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON>, who was digging excavations for new houses. Bombs dropped during the war that failed to go off are periodically unearthed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The East End was especially heavily bombed by the Germans during the war in a bid to cripple the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> docks. Police cordoned off the area and authorities evacuated people from their homes around the Sidney Street housing project. Those evacuated stayed with friends and relatives or at local council offices that were hurridly turned into temporary shelters. Twenty roads into the area also were closed to traffic.
