<HEAD>Soviet Defector's Saga To Freedom In Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When Soviet Jewish scientist <PERSON> Yakov </PERSON> <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> contacted <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> last week to say he wanted to defect, little did he know the complications he faced. First, he was told, `` Prove you are Jewish'' _ a serious problem because <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> had left his identity card thousands of miles away in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. What followed was a nightmarish saga of wrong airports, problematic telephones, delays and mixed directions _ proving to <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> it was n't as easy to defect as he may have thought. <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON>, a 48-year-old mathematician and computer expert, told the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Yediot </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ahronot </ORGANIZATION> he first thought of defecting while attending the scientific seminar as part of a six-member <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> delegation. `` I thought this was the chance to reach <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. ... Who knows if this opportunity would ever be repeated,'' he said in the interview published Thursday. <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> decided to phone Israeli diplomats in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. But the task proved complicated. `` I did not want to phone from the hotel and I was looking for public telephones. But soon I discovered you can not use a coin for every telephone and that for some you need a magnetic card,'' <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> said. Contact was finally established. But then came the Israeli demand: `` Prove that you are Jewish.'' <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON>'s Soviet-issued identity card, which he left behind in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, stated he was Jewish. But the passport he carried made no mention of his religion. According to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s Law of Return, all Jews are eligible for automatic Israeli citizenship. `` They asked: ` What Jewish holidays do you remember?''' <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> recalled. `` I told them with a stressed Yiddish accent: <PERSON> Rosh </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashana </PERSON> -LRB- the Jewish New Year -RRB-, Yom Kippur -LRB- the Day of Atonement -RRB-, and of course Shavuot -LRB- a holiday celebrating the spring harvest -RRB-'' he said. The officials were not immediately convinced. But the next day, when <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> called back, officials told him to take a taxi to <LOCATION> Orly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and go to the El Al -LRB- <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s airline -RRB- counter. <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> left all his belongings at a hotel, toured the Quai D'Orsay museum and left for the airport. But there were more problems ahead. `` They only forgot to tell me that <LOCATION> Orly </LOCATION> is divided in two, West and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, with the first one designated for internal flights only,'' he told <ORGANIZATION> Yediot </ORGANIZATION>. When <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> finally reached his destination, time was running out. `` I ... could not find the El Al counter. Then I started to walk around slowly, and gradually saw the word ` Tel Aviv' appearing on display screens,'' the bespectacled, gray-haired <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> said Thursday on <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>. He said he passed through French passport control with the help of an <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> official, who issued him an Israeli visa. Then he was brought to an empty plane. `` They told me that I can relax now, that this is <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> territory,'' he said. Take-off was delayed for what seemed an endless 30 minutes, <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> said. Once the plane took off, he destroyed a piece of paper on which he had written the number of his <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> contacts in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, as they had ordered. `` At -LRB- <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>'s -RRB- <LOCATION> Ben </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gurion </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, two men were waiting for me. One of them asked: `` Why did you arrive alone? You could ask for a visa and bring along your family.'' <PERSON> Kogan </PERSON> left behind his wife, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, and two sons, aged 7 and 10. He told <ORGANIZATION> Yediot </ORGANIZATION> he believed nothing would happen to them under the more liberal policies of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. He said he decided to defect because he felt progress in his scientific career at a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> institute was stymied due to treatment of Jews in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He told <ORGANIZATION> Yediot </ORGANIZATION> that money played no role _ both he and his wife were highly paid, lived in a three-room apartment considered a luxury by Soviet standards and owned a summer house near a forest. `` During all those years, I never asked to emigrate to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. I knew I would be refused,'' apparently on grounds that he knew state secrets, he said.
