<SECOND>PM-Kenya-Map,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil May Have Fueled Kenyan-Sudanese Clash Of the Cartographers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Call it the Muddle of the Maps or the Clash of the Cartographers, but <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> are at it again over a disputed area of dismal swamp and desert. The dispute goes back years, but neither side appeared to be paying much attention to it until recently, and a discovery of oil may have roiled their dispute over soil. In 1914, the British drew a straight line marking <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s northwestern border with <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> But in 1938, the British, who then ruled the East African nations, decided to give <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> administrative control of a triangular piece of land north of the <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> border. The area, known as the <ORGANIZATION> Elemi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Triangle </ORGANIZATION>, contained 1,393 square miles of seemingly worthless land and was home to the nomadic <LOCATION> Turkana </LOCATION> tribe, which was constantly raiding and being raided by other tribes from <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION>. The British administration in <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s capital, was unable to police the raiders and handed over administration of the area to authorities in the Kenyan capital of <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>, which was much closer. The 1938 agreement resulted in a new line on the map, this one putting the triangle in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>. There the matter rested until 1956, when <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> gained its independence, followed by <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> seven years later. The newly independent governments began drawing their own maps _ <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s with the original 1914 straight line, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s with the triangular border. `` From that time on,'' said <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s charge d'affaires in <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Yousuf </PERSON>, `` We have had two opinions.'' <PERSON> Yousuf </PERSON> told reporters Friday that a joint border commission met in the late 1970s but failed to resolve the matter, and the dispute once again faded. But last year, <PERSON> Yousuf </PERSON> said, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> published a new map that not only included the Elemi Triangle within its borders but enlarged the triangle by 2,489 square miles. <PERSON> Yousuf </PERSON> said he called the news conference `` to clarify the position of the <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> government.'' He was not, he insisted, discussing `` our borders with <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> through the press.'' But most of the argument has been waged through reporters. The newly revived dispute began with a front-page story in Monday's <ORGANIZATION> Kenya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, an English-language daily published in <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION> by the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Kenya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> party. Headlined, `` It's a Map of Provocation,'' the story noted that thousands of maps published by a Scottish company, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartholomew </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Son </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Edenburgh </LOCATION>, showed the straight 1914 border between <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. The next day, the newspaper's top story carried the banner headline, `` <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> Claims Kenyan Soil.'' On Wednesday, at a reception for foreign journalists, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ouko </PERSON>, made it a point to mention the dispute He, too, said he would not discuss the matter in the press, but added, `` The Elemi Triangle is an integral part of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> and that's the way it will remain. The two governments have not officially discussed the problem anew. Pressed Friday at the news conference, <PERSON> Yousuf </PERSON> said he did n't `` have enough information as to who is doing what in this disputed area,'' but suggested <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> may have found oil in the region President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> arap </PERSON> <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> announced last month oil had been found in northern <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, but did not specify where.
