<HEAD>Lawmakers Consider Corrections For The Press</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bill aimed at compelling newspapers and broadcasters to publish corrections of errors moved ahead in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION>, but legislators said it has little chance of final success. The bill, introduced by opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> lawmaker <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Worthington </PERSON>, proposes a statutory right for members of the public to correct inaccuracies about them in the news media. Corrections would have to be given the same prominence as the original mistake. <PERSON> Worthington </PERSON> said his Right of Reply bill was needed because of what he called the `` deterioration in standards of some sections of the press.'' He said the bill, which was unopposed Friday in its second reading, was not an attack on press freedom but an attack on the few editors and proprietors who abused their power. Legislators said the government was neutral about the Right of Reply Bill, so it would not have any priority on the crowded parliamentary agenda. They said time was likely to run out before the bill was examined in committee or in the crucial third reading. After being approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION>, the bill would then have to go to the House of Lords. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Renton </PERSON>, a Home Office junior minister speaking for the government, said scandal had been used to sell newspapers for hundreds of years. `` But ... we have a number of reservations about both the statutory control of the press and about the procedures set forth in the bill,'' <LOCATION> Renton </LOCATION> said. Labor legislator <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Clwyd </PERSON>, a journalist, said the bill was necessary to protect the public from what she called the excesses of the tabloid press. Two other bills dealing w