<HEAD>Study: Milk Of Canadian Eskimo Women Has Highest PCB Level In World</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The milk of nursing Eskimo women in northern <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> has a higher level of PCBs than that of women anywhere in the world, according to a university study published today. PCBs, or polychlorinated biphenyls, have been linked to cancer and skin rashes. The 1987 study at <ORGANIZATION> Laval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ste-Foy </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, obtained by the daily <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Devoir </ORGANIZATION> newspaper of <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, compared 24 samples of milk from <LOCATION> Eskimo </LOCATION> women in northern <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> to that of 48 women from southern <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, some from an industrial suburb of <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and the rest from <LOCATION> Baie-Comeau </LOCATION> on the shore of the lower St. Lawrence near an aluminum smelter. The fat in the milk of the Eskimo women showed an average PCB concentration of 3.59 parts per million compared to 0.76 for the rest of the samples, the newspaper said. Some Eskimo women had a concentration of 14.7. Health and <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION>, the federal agency responsible for health regulations, has set a tolerance level of 1.5 parts per million. Eskimo women in northern <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> tend to breast feed their babies for up to 23 months. Their diet for centuries has included large amounts of fish and animal fat. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Devoir </PERSON> quoted the study as saying an Eskimo child nursed by a mother whose milk has the average amount of <ORGANIZATION> PCB </ORGANIZATION> contamination would have imbibed enough of the toxic chemical within a year to show observable effects such as skin problems, liver complaints and problems with their immune system. Among women whose milk is highly contaminated, such effects might appear after four or five months, the newspaper said. The authors of the study say the PCBs in the area enter the environment from industrial waste poured into rivers and coastal waters and could come from as far away as the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Dewailly </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Laval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s hospital center, who directed research for the study, was quoted as telling <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Devoir </PERSON> that fish in the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lawrence </LOCATION> river `` are more contaminated than those in the north. `` But we southerners eat a lot less fish than the Inuit -LRB- Eskimo -RRB-,'' he said. The Laval scientists plan to monitor the subjects and their children for the next year, the newspaper said.
