More than 8,500 people have been killed in the 5-year separatist insurgency by militants in the Tamil minority. Extremists from the Sinhalese majority, angered by the government's peace overtures to the Tamils, have killed more than 900 people, mostly government supporters, the past 18 months. The government says <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has begun to withdraw Indian troops sent here in 1987 to disarm Tamils under terms of a failed peace pact. The Indian troops are estimated at 44,000. Both Tamil and Sinhalese extremists have vowed to violently disrupt parliamentary elections Feb. 15. Speaking in Sinhala, English and Tamil, <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> warned, `` Elements who seek to obstruct or destroy the democratic process will not be tolerated by the vast majority of freedom-loving Sri Lankans.'' `` Let us join hands in amity and unity to make our motherland a land of peace and prosperity,'' he said. The Tamils, who are mainly Hindu, make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s population. They claim discrimination by the mainly Buddhist Sinhalese, who are 75 percent of the population and dominate the government and military.
