<HEAD>John Cassavetes, Actor, Innovative Director, Dead At 59</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cassavetes </PERSON>, the actor and filmmaker whose innovative, unconventional movies such as `` A Woman Under the Influence'' and `` Faces'' drew both disdain and praise, has died at age 59. <PERSON> Cassavetes </PERSON>, who had been in poor health for three years, died Friday at <ORGANIZATION> Cedars-Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> of complications resulting from cirrhosis of the liver, said his publicist, <PERSON> Esme </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandlee </PERSON>. At his side was <PERSON> Gena </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowlands </PERSON>, his wife of 30 years and star of many of his films, including `` A Woman Under the Influence,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Chandlee </PERSON>. `` He was one of the most powerful and original filmmakers who ever lived. He broke ground in the way films are made,'' said actor <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Falk </PERSON>, a close friend who appeared with <PERSON> Cassavetes </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Gazarra </PERSON> in the 1969 film `` Husbands'' about three men drunkenly facing their own mortality after the death of a friend. <PERSON> Cassavetes </PERSON>, one of only four entertainers nominated for Academy Awards in three categories, was outspoken about the film industry and never afraid to praise his own work. `` I would put my pictures up against anybody's in this world,'' he said in a 1980 interview. `` Certainly in my own day I bow to no one. I do n't think there's another director in the world who works harder to make better films than I do.'' <PERSON> Cassavetes </PERSON> was nominated as best writer for his original screenplay for `` Faces'' in 1968; as best supporting actor in `` The Dirty Dozen'' in 1967; and as best director for `` A Woman Under the Influence'' in 1974. `` A Woman Under the Influence,'' was his favorite and also his most critically and commercially successful film. It won Miss <PERSON> Rowlands </PERSON> a Golden Globe award as best actress and an Academy Award nomination for best actress. As an actor, one of <PERSON> Cassavetes </PERSON>' best-known roles was in `` <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON>'s Baby,'' a 1968 film starring <PERSON> Mia </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrow </PERSON>, in which he played the husband of a woman who conceives a baby by the devil. He also starred with <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowlands </PERSON>, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarandon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Ringwald </PERSON> in `` Tempest,'' director <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazursky </PERSON>'s film adaptation of <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s play. <PERSON> Cassavetes </PERSON> made his directorial debut in 1960, when he helmed the well-received `` Shadows,'' an all-improvised `` cinema verite'' movie that borrowed heavily from the French New Wave movement and was produced on a spartan $ 40,000 budget. The movie was about a fair-skinned black girl living in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with her two brothers. He then directed two <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> films _ `` Too Late Blues'' with <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Darin </PERSON> and `` A Child Is Waiting'' with <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Garland </PERSON> and <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Lancaster </PERSON>. The failures of those films brought him back to being his own boss, using small film crews and filming on location. <PERSON> Cassavetes </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on Dec. 9, 1929, and grew up poor. His break in acting came when he played a brooding young bullfighter in a production of the old `` Omnibus'' TV series in 1953. That led to TV roles in `` Playhouse 90,'' `` Studio One,'' `` Kraft Theater'' and `` Climax.'' He made his movie debut in `` The Night Holds Terror'' in 1955. <PERSON> Cassavetes </PERSON> and Miss <PERSON> Rowlands </PERSON> were married in March 1958 and their careers were seldom separate after that. They had three children: <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON>, <PERSON> Alexandra </PERSON> and <PERSON> Zoe </PERSON>. Private funeral services were scheduled Monday at Westwood Memorial Park.
