<HEAD>Man Released After 11 Years In Jail Without Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials today released a carpenter who was arrested for communist activities and held for 11 years without trial, an opposition member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Cheah </PERSON> <PERSON> Swee </PERSON> <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> was released from the <LOCATION> Kamunting </LOCATION> detention camp, 120 miles north of the capital, after being held under <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>'s Internal Security Act, said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Lam </PERSON> <PERSON> Thye </PERSON>, secretary-general of the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, in a statement, urged the release of other detainees held under the act, including opposition parliamentary leader Lim Kit Siang. <PERSON> Cheah </PERSON>, 40, was arrested for communist subversive activities. The banned <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Malaysia </ORGANIZATION> has 1,500 guerrillas fighting from the jungles mainly along the <LOCATION> Thailand-Malaysia </LOCATION> border. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, who is a member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, called on the government to release <PERSON> Lim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lim </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Lim </PERSON> <PERSON> Guan </PERSON> <PERSON> Eng </PERSON>, who have been in jail without trial under the Internal Security Act since October 1987. The two, both members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, are the only remaining prisoners of 106 political leaders ordered arrested in 1987 by Prime Minister <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohamad </PERSON>, who claimed their actions and speeches were increasing racial tensions between the Malays and Chinese. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said about 64 people overall are still being held without trial under the Internal Security Act. About 550 were detained when <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> became prime minister in 1981. <PERSON> Mahathir </PERSON> called for a review and released most of them. In December, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> criticized the act, which empowers authorities to order preventive detention without trial for activities deemed extremely and imminently dangerous to the state and the public. The London-based human rights group said the act fails to state clear criteria for identifying such activities, and authorities have not distinguished between violent activities that threaten national security and non-violent activities that do not involve such a threat. Amnesty requested a review of the security act. Malaysian laws are `` seriously inadequate'' to safeguard against arbitrary arrest, detention without trial, torture or other degrading treatment, it said.
