en radical groups have threatened to disrupt <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s funeral, which will be attended by dignitaries from over 130 nations, including President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Prince <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. More than 30,000 police will be mobilized to ensure their safety. Ultraleftists claim the monarchy supports Japanese imperialism, and they are protesting the state funeral because they say <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> should be treated as a war criminal for his role in World War II. <PERSON> Fujiwara </PERSON>, who described himself as a `` ranking member'' of the <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Core </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Faction </ORGANIZATION>, refused to say whether <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is being singled out as a target but said the American leader's attendance at the funeral `` is inexcusable.'' The faction, seen by police as a serious threat to funeral security, is believed to have the capability of firing missiles more than 2 -LCB- miles. After the 1986 <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> summit of industrialized nations, it claimed responsibility for launching missiles that overshot a state guest house where Western leaders were meeting. `` It is natural to assume that our technology has improved since then,'' <PERSON> Fujiwara </PERSON> said. He refused to elaborate.
