<HEAD>Non-Combatants Say Rebel Leaders Should Close Their Ranks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOGHARI, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Azaldin </PERSON>, a schoolteacher from the eastern city of <LOCATION> Ghazni </LOCATION>, says he does n't care who rules his ravaged country, as long as the fighting stops. He is typical of many Afghans who have braved a decade of brutal fighting between communist forces and Moslem rebels called mujahedeen. <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> leaders, the seven most powerful of whom are based in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, are fighting for an Islamic republic of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> but so far have failed to agree on how to slice any postwar political pie. `` They have had no unity,'' said <PERSON> Azaldin </PERSON>, 37, who uses just one name. `` Each of them wants power. But seven kings or presidents in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> is impossible.'' <PERSON> Fazle </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON>, an elderly merchant who sells spices and grain from a grimy adobe shop in this small settlement, says he does n't know one guerrilla chief from another `` We do n't know much about them. We follow the local mujahedeen commanders,'' he said. <PERSON> Fazle </PERSON> said his sympathy for the guerrillas forced him to abandon his original shop in the communist-held center of <LOCATION> Ghazni </LOCATION>, about 75 miles southwest of the Afghan capital. With the Feb. 15 deadline for the final Soviet troop withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> drawing near, mujahedeen political leaders have been trying to reach a political consensus. They have tentative plans for a Feb. 10 `` shura,'' or consultative council to convene in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, but its composition remains uncertain. Invitees include representatives of rebels based in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. These guerrillas belong to the Shiite Moslem sect, which comprises about 17 percent of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s population. The majority of Afghans are Sunnis, as are the Pakistan-based rebel groups. Both sides have yet to agree on their proportional representation in the council. The shura's main task is to name a transitional government that can step into power if the guerrillas topple the ruling <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zai </PERSON>, a 78-year-old former farmer who now runs errands for the guerrillas, says that for him, politics plays second to peace. `` For me, it's not a problem of who it is who leads <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, as long as the people like him and choose him,'' <PERSON> Zai </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fazle </PERSON> said that if individual guerrilla leaders make a grab for power after the Soviet withdrawal, they will get little support from battle-weary Afghans. `` We just want an Islamic government,'' he said. `` We did n't fight for anybody but God, Islam and our country Even our small children understand this.''
