<HEAD>With AM-Gesell's Dilemma Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>North Trial Judge Called Stern, Smart, Fair, Not Lacking In Confidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Well before <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s trial got under way in Courtroom 6, Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> asked how long it would last, telling lawyers `` far more important matters'' awaited his attention. Sparring from the bench with defense lawyers and prosecutors alike, the energetic 78-year-old federal district judge obviously relishes the limelight and legal challenges posed by the first criminal trial in the Iran-Contra affair. But despite the national attention given the case, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> took pains at the Jan. 9 hearing to remind the lawyers that he will treat it like just another criminal matter on his crowded docket. `` It has become increasingly urgent for me to know how long this case is going to take,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said at the hearing. `` There are a substantial number of litigants with _ I think _ far more important matters pending who want to be heard. `` I've got all kinds of problems in terms of the work of the court as an institution,'' said <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>, who unlike most judges his age has refused to take a reduced caseload by going on `` senior status.'' Told the trial could last four or five months, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> replied, `` It will be a wonderful summer.'' Highly regarded for his intellect and ability to conduct a difficult trial, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> is known among <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyers as being impatient with slipshod pleadings and arguments. `` You better be prepared, but he gives you a fair hearing on everything,'' said attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, a former bar association president who has tried a number of civil cases before <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>. Others note a touch of intellectual arrogance in <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>, the son of a noted <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> child psychologist. `` Sometimes wrong, never in doubt,'' said one attorney, echoing _ on condition of anonymity _ a sentiment expressed by other colleagues in the local bar. `` He does a lot of thinking out loud, a sign of self-confidence of which he is not lacking.'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>'s habit of expressing his thoughts from the bench has sent many a reporter scurrying to the telephone with excited accounts about the judge's latest doubts about the future of the Iran-Contra case. At the outset of jury selection, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said the difficulty finding prospective jurors who had no knowledge of <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s immunized congressional testimony raised questions about `` the triability of the case.'' Yet after five days, the judge managed to find 32 prospective jurors for a planned pool of 50, from which the panel will be selected. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> can also be hot tempered as he was when he threatened an <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> reporter with a contempt-of-court citation for airing an account of jury selection that he said `` appears to be a deliberate effort'' to disrupt the process. The judge's storm of vituperation quickly passed and there has been no further mention of contempt proceedings against the television reporter, <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>'s experience with big cases and troubling issues throughout his 20-year career on the bench no doubt figured in the decision by <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the chief judge of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> here, to assign the Iran-Contra cases to him. Throughout the pre-trial maneuverings several judges expressed the view that if any jurist could bring the difficult case to trial it would be <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>. `` He is just very much in control,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffress </PERSON>, a criminal defense lawyer who clerked for <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> in the early 1970s. `` I would certainly say he has a dominating personality. He is and remains in control of what goes on in his court.'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> has had his share of other famous cases, notably the Watergate plumbers case in 1974, which involved the conspiracy to break into the office of a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> psychiatrist to get the patient records of <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellsberg </PERSON>, who leaked the Pentagon Papers to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> refused in 1971 to enjoin <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> from publishing its version of the secret <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> study of the Vietnam War. He was the only federal judge who refused to grant the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s requests for injunctions to delay newpaper publication of the Pentagon Papers _ a position vindicated by a unanimous <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision in the case. A year earlier, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> had enjoined the Government Printing Office from publishing a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> report listing 65 `` radical revolutionary'' campus speakers. The judge found it had served no `` legislative purpose and was issued solely for exposure for intimidation.'' After attending <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> as an undergraduate and law student, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> came to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> during the New Deal and went to work at the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> for <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, who later became a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justice. At the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> successfully investigated a major Wall Street investment scandal _ an episode <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> cites in his memoirs. Later, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> became a partner for the celebrated <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> law firm of <PERSON> Covington </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Burling </ORGANIZATION>, making his mark as an anti-trust lawyer. With his rosy cheeks, the white-haired jurist was once aptly described by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> as resembling a clean-shaven <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION>. Known among friends as a jovial raconteur, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> usually spends the month of August at his summer home on an island off the cost of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. On most weekends, he and his wife, <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON>, go to their dairy farm near <LOCATION> Leesburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, where he produces his own brand of honey that is sold in local stores and vegetable stands. <PERSON> Jeffress </PERSON> said <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> is not just a `` gentleman farmer who goes out and gets waited on, but a farmer who gets his feet dirty.''
