<FIRST>r w AM-PayRaise-Surveys     02-04 0833</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pay Raise-Surveys,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Pollster' Wright Gets More Feedback Than He Bargained For</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pay Raise Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> sent out a questionnaire on the pay raise issue to his colleagues last week, one came back with a cryptic note: `` <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Rayburn </PERSON> would not have sent out a survey like this.'' The reference to fellow <PERSON> Texan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rayburn </PERSON>, considered among the strongest <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> speakers in the century, was a pointed jab at <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> for failing to take command on the controversial issue and instead attempting to spread the blame by seeking the opinions of his colleagues. `` There were four who wrote on the survey something to the effect that ` This is a bum idea,''' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> conceded to reporters as he handed out the results of his poll last week. But he contended many more members were glad to be consulted on how to handle the recommended 51 percent pay hike. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s venture into the polling business, an apparent attempt to demonstrate that he was acting on behalf of a majority of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members to engineer a salary increase, appeared to have backfired in several ways. For one, the speaker failed to consult even his top leadership team before sending out the 12-question survey form. The leaders, in turn, were left scrambling to distance themselves from what they clearly considered a dubious idea. Some senior Democrats were bitter about the move. `` This has permanently hurt <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>,'' said one, speaking only on condition of anonymity. In addition, the confidential survey was sharply at odds with the outcomes of several public surveys conducted by the news media and interest groups. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said of 326 House members responding privately to his survey, 57 percent did not want to vote on the pay raise before it goes into effect at midnight Tuesday. But when The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> queried 105 lawmakers, 88 percent said they did want to vote before the deadline. In an informal poll of 278 members by the self-described consumer group <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION>, 265 _ 61 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> _ said on the record that they wanted a vote. `` Somebody's not telling the truth,'' said Public Citizen's <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>, an outspoken pay raise critic. `` For the speaker to expose members to a charge of lying is a very serious case of leadership run amok.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> intended the survey to bolster his strategy of letting the raise go into effect, then holding a vote to roll it back to 30 percent. But it instead showed the speaker could fall short of the two-thirds majority needed for a rollback under the expedited process he chose for bringing the issue to the floor. What the results did show was deep division among <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members over the entire issue of congressional pay and how it is set, and inconsistency between the answers to some questions. For example: _ Fifty-six percent favored and 44 percent opposed the process under which pay levels for lawmakers and top officials are recommended by an independent commission, proposed by the president and put in effect automatically unless both houses vote to cancel them. _ On the question of whether they would vote against any effort to rescind the raise entirely, 49 percent said yes and 46 percent said no. _ Asked if the 50 percent raise for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and similar increases for other top government jobs were `` fair and proper,'' 54 percent said yes. But asked more specifically about the amount of the increases, 56 percent said they were too high. _ A majority, 54 percent, opposed a vote before Wednesday on banning honoraria, such as fees for speaking before lobbying groups, and limiting the raise to 30 percent. But after Wednesday, and following an honoraria ban, 61 percent favored rolling back the pay raise to 30 percent. Only on one question were sentiments near unanimous: 98 percent said they would vote to ban honoraria if the pay raise goes into effect. The survey `` has put the heat on everybody, and it is n't going to go away,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Penny </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, one of the few Democrats willing to criticize the speaker publicly. `` This issue is going to leave a bad taste in the mouths of a lot of members, and eventually that's got to add up. Sooner or later, the good will is going to be gone.'' Some lawmakers observed that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> came into the fray over pay carrying heavy political baggage from two continuing <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Ethics <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> investigations into his conduct. One case, involving allegations the speaker abused his office while majority leader for financial gain, is expected to be resolved late this month. Whatever the outcome of that inquiry, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> will likely face another public pummeling led by his chief accuser, Rep. <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, R-Ga., and the fallout from the survey could hurt, said one prominent House Democrat `` In a matter of weeks, he'll be asking these same people to stand up for him against <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>,'' said the lawmaker.
