<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> ended a three-day visit to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on Saturday by announcing the nations will hold their first summit in 30 years in mid-May. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will travel to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> at the invitation of the Chinese for a meeting with senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>. Soviet sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the summit was tentatively scheduled for May 15. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tian </PERSON> <PERSON> Zengpei </PERSON>, however, said no date had been set and that the Chinese were `` studying the proposal'' for the May meeting. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> later flew to <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, for meetings with Pakistani leaders about the Soviet troop withdrawal from neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. At a news conference before his departure, <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> told him the summit would `` close the page on the past and open up a chapter on the future.'' In a move toward `` complete normalization'' of relations, diplomats and other officials are to discuss reducing military tensions along the 5,000-mile Soviet-Chinese border, he said. Western diplomats said the issue first came up when Chinese Foreign Minister <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Qichen </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in December. `` We hope at the summit we will be able to make progress in that important direction,'' <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said. He said the first step might be an agreement on advance notice of troop movements and military exercises, and then negotiations for disbanding offensive forces. In the 1950s, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> depended on Soviet technical and military aid and followed the Soviet lead in diplomatic policy. Relations between the countries soured in 1960 over ideological and strategic disputes, and they fought a brief border war in 1969. The Chinese agreed to discuss a summit last year after progress was made on what they call the `` three obstacles'' _ border tensions, Soviet aid for <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s invasion of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The last Soviet troops are supposed to be out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by Feb. 15. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has pledged to remove from <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> 200,000 Soviet troops, many now stationed along the Chinese border, and has said that most of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s 50,000 troops in <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> will be withdrawn. <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> was the first <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> foreign minister to visit <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 32 years. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s visit was the first by a Soviet foreign minister in 30 years and was designed to lay the groundwork for the summit. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> formally issued its invitation to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on Friday. `` Substantive progress has been made'' on obstacles that have stood in the way of a summit, Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Tian </PERSON> told reporters following <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s departure. `` This visit produced results.'' He said the two sides now agree that <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> should end its 10-year occupation of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> by September as promised and that there should be international supervision of the troop withdrawal. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> backs the anti-Vietnamese resistance in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and has demanded <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> pressure its ally, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, to pull out. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said better Sino-Soviet relations are the result of the countries' economic reforms and he envisioned increased trading between the nations. The countries are believed to want to ease tensions so they can concentrate less on military matters and more on rejuvenating their economies. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> flew to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, about 870 miles south of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, for the 90-minute meeting with <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> on Saturday morning. He said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s top leader was `` a very wise man who has a lot of rich experience.'' There have been rumors that the 84-year-old <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> is in failing health but <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said he appeared quite fit.
