<FIRST>r a AM-AntarcticAftermath Bjt   02-04 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Antarctic Aftermath, Bjt,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>Antarctic Oil Spill May Threaten Wildlife Research, Scientists Fear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil from a sunken ship off <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> threatens not only the environment in a pristine bay, but also wildlife research in a biologically rich area prized until now for its unspoiled state, scientists say. `` The paths of research that have been followed down there have been forever changed,'' said <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Talmadge </PERSON>. `` I think if you're a scientist in the year 2035, you've got to remember there was an oil spill.'' <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLaca </PERSON>, chief scientist of the foundation's polar programs, said the highly sensitive environment `` has been compromised in a way that we ca n't even evaluate right now.'' While the spill's effect on future research can not yet be determined, `` it's something I find personally disturbing,'' he said by telephone Friday from <LOCATION> Palmer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION>, a research outpost near the spill. The oil is leaking from an Argentine research and supply ship that ran aground Jan. 25. The ship is nearly submerged on shoals in the <LOCATION> Bismarck </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> just off the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION>, 600 miles from the tip of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Authorities said the ship carried at least 200,000 gallons of fuel oil in its tanks and more in drums lashed to the deck. American cleanup crews are expected to reach the site sometime this week. Some scientists said the effects of the spill may be magnified because it involved fuel oil, more dangerous to wildlife than crude oil, and because <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> conditions could slow the oil's decomposition The spill struck an area that has `` the largest and most diverse plant and animal populations of the continent,'' said <PERSON> Polly </PERSON> <PERSON> Penhale </PERSON>, manager of the science foundation's polar biology and medicine program. Apart from a large seal population, some 30,000 sea birds live in the area affected by the spill, including <ORGANIZATION> Adele </ORGANIZATION> and chinstrap penguins, cormorants, kelp gulls and giant petrels, <PERSON> Penhale </PERSON> said. `` It is one of the most spectacularly beautiful areas in the whole <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>,'' said Sayed Z. <PERSON> El-Sayed </PERSON>, an oceanography professor at <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> M </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> who has studied it for 25 years. Most plants and animals live on islands off the mainland, where the science foundation operates <ORGANIZATION> Palmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> on a spit of rock. Scientists have already seen oil-covered and apparently lethargic seals, three dead penguins and disappearances of young nesting birds, <PERSON> DeLaca </PERSON> said. Thirty-eight of 40 penguins checked Friday bore traces of oil. Thousands of dead and dying krill, shrimplike crustaceans that are a key food for bigger animals, have shown up on beaches, he said. `` All the principal -LRB- penguin -RRB- rookeries here are now surrounded by fuel oil,'' he said. `` What its effect could be on the birds is anybody's guess.'' Birds can freeze to death if the oil disrupts their natural insulation, or be poisoned if they swallow oil while preening themselves or eating contaminated prey. Scientists have studied wildlife in the area for more than 20 years, focusing on birds and seals and also on such organisms as fish, kelp, krill and shelled animals called limpets. `` One of the main concerns of the scientists ... is that that area stay pristine, because we have a lot of environmental research that's going on,'' said <PERSON> Langdon </PERSON> <PERSON> Quetin </PERSON>, research biologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION>. `` It is one of the few areas in the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> we have good logistics to,'' he said. The spill `` will be the ruination of a good laboratory, at least in the near future, at least as a natural uncontaminated study area.'' Some scientists are particularly concerned about fish and other organisms kept in tanks at <LOCATION> Palmer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION>, which marine botanist <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Neushul </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION> calls `` probably the best marine biology laboratory in the Antarctic.'' The tanks draw seawater from the nearby harbor, and if oil contaminates that supply, the experiments might have to be stopped. Nobody knows yet whether that will be a problem, <PERSON> Penhale </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Neushul </PERSON> said one factor boding poorly for the area's wildlife is that the spill involved fuel oil, which is much more toxic than crude oil because it can damage biological tissue. <PERSON> Neushul </PERSON>, who investigated a spill of partially refined oil off <LOCATION> Baja </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> 30 years ago, said that spill caused mass deaths of fish, starfish, sea urchins and other animals. The same may happen to similar animals in the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION>, he said. In the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> spill, the environment took 17 years to recover, he said. Recovery in <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> may take even longer because bacteria there will need a long time to break the oil down, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Dayton </PERSON>, professor of marine ecology at the <ORGANIZATION> Scripps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanography </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jolla </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. After years of studying wildlife in a pristine environment, researchers are now turning to monitor how the wildlife responds to the oil spill, <PERSON> Talmadge </PERSON> said `` This disaster is the experiment nobody wanted,'' he said.
