<HEAD>Nearly 140,000 AIDS Cases Reported Worldwide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> says 7,000 new AIDS cases were reported last month, raising the worldwide total to nearly 140,000. Most of the increase was due to updated reports on acquired immune deficiency syndrome from the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION> said Friday in its monthly update on the spread of the deadly disease. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> reported more than half of the new cases, nearly 4,000. WHO estimated the real number of adult cases was between 350,000 and 400,000 by the end of last year, with sub-Saharan <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> thought to account for more than half the victims The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agency noted that the accuracy of reports on AIDS patients varies widely between countries and continents. WHO said 139,886 cases were reported from 144 countries by Jan. 31, a rise of 6,910 over a month earlier. Thirty-three countries said they had no cases. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> territory, reported its first victims: two as of Aug. 1. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has recorded 60 percent of all AIDS cases, reported 3,965 new cases last month. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, with the highest total and case rate in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, reported an increase of 781 to 5,655 cases. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> reported 452 new victims, bringing its total to 3,008. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s figure rose to 2,165 with the report of 315 new cases. AIDS is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring.
