of caution, and that's a judgment call that I'm making myself.'' The committee also is conscious of its experience with <PERSON> Melvyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON>, a key figure in the Pentagon procurement investigation. <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> was nominated in 1981 as assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and later confirmed. Tower, committee chairman at the time, said the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> refused the panel's request to see the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report on <LOCATION> Paisley </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said if they had known of the allegations against <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> they would have withheld approval until the charges had been checked. The ranking members of the 1989 committee would like to avoid a similar incident. `` It's not over till it's over,'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said Thursday. `` The investigation is not over until all serious allegations have been checked, and that's the process we always follow.''
