<HEAD>Plant-Closings Debate Still Raging as Law Takes Effect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <ORGANIZATION> Levi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strauss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> announced last week it would close a denim jacket plant in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, it gave 140 workers 90 days' paid notice. It was a better cushion than most workers have been getting when plants close down. <PERSON> Levi </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> was following voluntary policies in place since 1984, guaranteeing workers advance notice of pending plant closings. Notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs, however, is now the law. Plant closing legislation passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year took full effect Saturday, with business and labor still debating its impact and both sides predicting a flood of lawsuits. `` The companies are mystified at how complicated this law really is,'' said <PERSON> Renee </PERSON> <PERSON> Reymond </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>. `` The labor attorneys certainly are poised and ready for business.'' Supporters say the law will not hurt business and gives workers a time to prepare for job loss. Federal figures show 64 percent of the nearly 2 million workers idled annually receive no notice. Opponents maintain the law represents a threat to industry. `` The threat is one of government fines, lawsuits, back pay and benefits expenses, loss of market image and costly training and adjustment problems,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> declared recently. Then-President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> allowed the measure to become law in August without his signature, despite having earlier called it `` a ticking time bomb in the back seat of any medium-sized or larger company.'' Pressure from then presidential candidate <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was said to have influenced <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. On Capitol Hill, supporters of the concept still say it was long overdue. `` The ` chicken littles' have been proven wrong again,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass. `` The sky did not fall. Enactment of this law was a triumph of reason over ideology and American workers will now receive the notice they deserve.'' Provisions of the law call for it to take effect Saturday, but some employers have started early on the theory that courts may eventually hold that shutdowns up to 60 days beforehand were covered. <ORGANIZATION> Lehigh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Structural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Allentown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, for example, announced Jan. 24 that its 184 employees would be laid off after current orders are filled. President <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON> said in a telephone interview last week that the company was observing the 60-day notice period. `` Nobody can seem to tell us what the law is, so we're being safe,'' <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON> said. A random survey of a dozen companies that have announced shutdowns or major layoffs in the past two months found that nearly all had given their workers at least 60 days' notice, most because of company policies in place before the law was passed. For example: _ <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said last week it would close a pizza plant in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> and a potato flake plant in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, idling 334 workers who got 60 days' notice _ <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> recently announced plans to close two facilities in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, area, one with 500 workers, the other 130 Many are being offered jobs elesewhere in the company and <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> has a policy of giving a minimum 90-day notice, spokesman <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON> said. _ <ORGANIZATION> Mack </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trucks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> five weeks ago announced it was laying off 300 workers at its <LOCATION> Macungie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, assembly plant, but since has said only about half that many would lose their jobs <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said the union workers had been told of the initial layoff plans several months before the announcement. `` Our policy has been that we're not going to wait until February to be in compliance,'' she said. `` We decided to treat it as if it was in effect immediately.'' But about 130 workers at a microwave plant in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.D. </LOCATION>, who lost their jobs Friday got only one week notice. The layoffs do not appear to be covered by the law _ even under the liberal interpretation of its effective date. The law requires advance notice of plant closings by employers with at least 100 full-time workers if the shutdown will cost 50 or more of those employees their jobs. In the case of layoffs, notices are required if the number of affected workers totals 33 percent of the company's employees or 500 _ whichever figure is lower. In <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, Microwave Products of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> began the year with about 650 workers at its plant and in January laid off 155. That left the company with about 495 workers. By laying off 130 workers the company fell about 35 short of the 33 percent threshold. `` It was reviewed,'' company spokesman <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said when asked about the plant closing law. He said the company's position was that the law did not carry weight until after Saturday and also noted that regardless of the effective date the layoffs did not meet the threshold.
