<FIRST>u w AM-Gesell'sDilemma Bjt   02-04 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gesell's Dilemma, Bjt,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Same Judge, Same Legal Dilemmas in North Trial and Watergate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The intense publicity, the fight over secret documents, the legal dilemmas posed at the trial of <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> rouse memories of a celebrated Watergate trial at which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> also presided. As he began jury selection last week in the trial of the former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide, the white-haired judge with the no-nonsense manner followed procedures he used more than 14 years ago for the so-called Plumbers trial. A defendant in that case was an aide from an earlier White House _ <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ehrlichman </PERSON>, former chief domestic adviser to <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. Courtroom No. 6 on the second floor of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Courthouse </ORGANIZATION> was the scene of that trial, as it is the North trial. There are other similarities. Like North, <PERSON> Ehrlichman </PERSON> was a prodigious note-taker who contended his files were essential to his defense. Like North, <PERSON> Ehrlichman </PERSON> had starred on television as a featured witness at hearings watched by millions of Americans. Like North, <PERSON> Ehrlichman </PERSON>'s role in a White House scandal was the subject of front-page stories that intrigued a nation for months before his case came to trial. Despite the torrent of publicity, it took <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> just two days to seat a jury for the Plumbers trial _ named for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> unit established to plug leaks of classified information. Only three potential jurors were dismissed because they said they doubted they could render an impartial verdict. But the North trial presents <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> with a problem he did n't face 14 years ago. <PERSON> Ehrlichman </PERSON> did n't have immunity when he testified before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Watergate committee. <PERSON> North </PERSON> did have a guarantee his testimony before the congressional Iran-Contra committee could n't be used against him. Dozens of prospective jurors have been dismissed from the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> trial because they said they heard <PERSON> North </PERSON> testify to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that he committed crimes. The search for an untainted jury in the North trial `` is exacerbated by the immunity,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben-Veniste </PERSON>, one of the Watergate prosecutors. `` This case has more problems than any I've ever seen,'' said <PERSON> Ben-Veniste </PERSON>, who played a leading role in the trial of former <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administration officials convicted on charges stemming from the break-in at <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in the Watergate office building. What has struck some observers of the North trial is the search for people who had no curiosity about the Iran-Contra scandal when it was unfolding in televised hearings. `` Whether they will differ from normal, average jurors remains to be seen,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON>, D-Ala., a former state supreme court judge who served on the Iran-Contra committee `` If a man never saw anything of it, what type of individual is he?'' `` I would n't want people who lived in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the seat of government, on that jury who were so uninformed,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Moffitt </PERSON>, a criminal defense attorney. The magnitude of <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>'s problem was illustrated by the case of a prospective juror disqualified because she worked at a <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> store where dozens of TV sets were turned on when <PERSON> North </PERSON> testified in July 1987. The woman has not watched the testimony, but her exposure to it was such that the judge decided to remove her from the panel of potential jurors. Documents are another common issue. In both cases, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> made extraordinary appeals to the president, but the tone of each was quite different. In the North case, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> urged President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to decide whether massive amounts of classified information <PERSON> North </PERSON> contended was vital to his defense could be released. `` The court has a very limited role,'' said <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>, adding that the Constitution provides that it is up to the president `` not North or any witness, to protect the prerogatives of the president's office if he deems them unduly threatened. North had sought some 40,000 pages of documents. When the president refused to release material _ saying `` these are things that are national security secrets'' _ conspiracy charges against <PERSON> North </PERSON> were dropped. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> never implied he thought the White House was withholding material simply to block prosecution of the man <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had once referred to as `` a national hero.'' The judge's attitude was very different when he came into conflict with the <ORGANIZATION> Nixon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> over <PERSON> Ehrlichman </PERSON>'s request to have access to his files. When the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> said that only the defendant, not his lawyer, would be allowed into the room where the files were kept, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> responded scathingly. `` I do n't see how I can agree to a procedure that is so totally offensive,'' he said. `` It is offensive, sir, it borders on obstruction,'' he told <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clair </PERSON>, the lawyer representing <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> at various proceedings then underway to examine the president's role in Watergate.
