<HEAD>Steel Employees Get Closing Notice; But Jobs Still Leaving</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE OWEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> once lost a job with less than a week's notice, so he appreciated getting two months' warning of the closing of <ORGANIZATION> Lehigh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Structural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s fabricating plant. That notice under a new federal law is only so much help, though. `` You're out of a job no matter how you look at it,'' <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, 23, said Friday in a drizzle at the lunch truck outside the 70-year-old factory. <ORGANIZATION> Lehigh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Structural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullen </PERSON>, citing inability to compete in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> with Canadian companies, announced Jan. 24 that the company would shut down most of its <LOCATION> Allentown </LOCATION> operations permanently by March 24, putting about 185 of 225 employees out of work. A new law that took effect Saturday requires companies with 100 or more full-time employees to give 60 days' notice of plant closings or major layoffs. Under some interpretations of the law, <ORGANIZATION> Lehigh </ORGANIZATION> had to give notice even before the Feb. 4 effective date, and the company provided it. `` It's not like you can come in one day and the doors are locked,'' <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> said. The notice, he said, means `` now we've got a chance'' to look for other jobs. A union official said that notice may not be a big help for many of his members, but said company officials have been straightforward. `` They're abiding by the plant-closing law. They've been really cooperative,'' secretary-treasurer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kontier </PERSON> of Local 548 of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bridge </ORGANIZATION>, Structural and Ornamental Ironworkers union. The law does n't require that each employee receives 60 days' notice, because some employees may be laid off before a plant closes entirely `` They just said the plant's shutting down. Then I got a three-day layoff notice,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelby </PERSON>, a punch operator at the plant for five years who was one of seven or eight workers laid off Friday. He said he thought he should have received more notice. Even with 60 days' notice, job counseling under way and retraining to start soon, <PERSON> Kontier </PERSON> said, the law may not get his members quickly back to work. He said they will first search in vain for jobs that pay near the steel plant's average $ 10 to $ 11 an hour, plus benefits including health insurance. He wants to see more government efforts to keep companies in business, particularly in making sure foreign companies do n't get an unfair advantage in markets. But those would be too late for this company. Gradual layoffs began in January and one fabricating shop closed a week ago, with another scheduled to close this week, said plant superintendent <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, who at 59 will be looking for a job himself. By the target closing date of the entire plant in April, the last shop will have finished the remaining steelwork for a 41-story building in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON> said about 30 employees will be needed for the last stage. The shutdown plans surprised <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, who began work at the plant last May. He liked the idea of the new law, but little did he know as politicians fussed over its passage last year that it would affect him. `` I had no feeling at all. When I started in May, I thought my job was set,'' said <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, who bought a house last September and was married in October. `` I thought I could retire here.'' `` My whole family worked here,'' he said. `` My grandfather was here when they opened the plant.''
