<HEAD>GAO Says Problems With New Bomber Persist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Major problems still plaguing the B-1B bomber may reduce its expected range and payload capability, says a report issued by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' investigative arm. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> concluded in its report that although the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has made progress in correcting certain deficiencies in the Rockwell-built bomber, problems in the bomber's performance persist `` Several areas critical to B-1B's mission performance have not yet been demonstrated,'' the report said. The review also said the cost of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> plane could be up to $ 400 million each if the service goes ahead with all the planned improvements. Those problems mean the B-1B may not have the range it was designed to have or be able to carry all the bombs and missiles planned for it, the report said. The bomber is designed to carry conventional and nuclear gravity bombs, cruise missiles and short-range attack missiles. Specifically, the report said the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has not made progress in resolving problems with the B-1B's defensive avionics. `` In short, it is now known that the defensive avionics can not meet specifications without a major redesign,'' the report said. The defensive avionics, or electronic countermeasures system, was designed to improve the bomber's probability of penetrating the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> by allowing the aircraft's crew to `` avoid, degrade and deceive the Soviet air defenses,'' the report said. The problems involve the system's radar warning receiver and processor function. The report also said that data for the bomber indicate that reported fuel leaks have for the most part remained the same over the last year. Elimination of the fuel leaks is probably not possible, according to the report, which noted that the fuel cells are part of the airframe and seals and joints are subjected to flight stress. The B-1, killed by then-President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> in 1977, was resurrected four years later by former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who said 100 of the swing-wing planes were needed to update the nation's aging force of nuclear-armed bombers. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> ordered 100 of the planes, at a cost of $ 20.5 billion. Three have crashed, leaving the service with 97 B-1Bs. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has already received all the B-1s it intends to buy and is now proceeding with plans to buy the radar-evading B-2 stealth bomber.
