 apology to the town, and to remain in <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> while awaiting sentencing. <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> reduced bail on both theft charges to $ 2,500 each and <PERSON> Keyser </PERSON> posted bail after Friday's hearing. Residents in <LOCATION> Kake </LOCATION>, a timber and fishing town about 75 miles south of <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Kupreanof </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, became suspicious of <PERSON> Keyser </PERSON> shortly after he took the $ 44,000-a-year job. They accused him of overspending and criticized him for refusing to release his resume for public inspection. A police records check in December revealed the outstanding <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> warrant. Interviews with prosecutors and city officials in several states revealed that at least 19 of <PERSON> Keyser </PERSON>'s jobs since 1980 have been with city or county governments. Documents and the interviews also showed <PERSON> Keyser </PERSON> used false information while obtaining at least 11 jobs. <PERSON> Kake </PERSON> officials have said they hired him because of an impressive resume and people who gave glowing references. But they now believe the resume and the references who were contacted by telephone were fraudulent. Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Ketchikan </LOCATION> said Friday that <LOCATION> Pikeville </LOCATION> officials probably would dismiss their charge against <PERSON> Keyser </PERSON>. Last month, <LOCATION> Pikeville </LOCATION> city commissioners asked the prosecutor there to drop the charge, but the prosecutor said at the time that he wanted to continue to press the case. In <LOCATION> Pikeville </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Keyser </PERSON> is accused of theft by deception for failure to reimburse the city for $ 697 in travel expenses. <PERSON> Keyser </PERSON> declined to comment on the Kake case after the hearing. He said he planned to do community and church volunteer work while awaiting sentencing. In an interview in December, he maintained his innocence and said the charges were the result of a conspiracy in <LOCATION> Pikeville </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Keyser </PERSON> accused the news media and officials of seeking to make an example of him.
