<HEAD>Sullivan Says Unpaid Leave Will Avoid Appearance of Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cabinet nominee <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said Saturday he would take an unpaid leave of absence from his medical school while serving as health and human services secretary to avoid any appearance of a conflict of interest. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, had wanted to maintain his ties to the school with a paid leave, but he withdrew the request after the White House raised questions about the arrangement. `` I intend to preclude even the remotest possibility of any appearance that my actions as secretary might be influenced due to any outside income,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said in a statement released by the White House. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said he has asked the medical school's executive committee to grant him an unpaid leave of absence while he serves in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. White House spokesman <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said an unpaid leave would mean the school `` would suspend any salary payments while he served as secretary of <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> earns about $ 170,000 a year from <LOCATION> Morehouse </LOCATION>, it was learned. The arrangement is designed to avoid any conflict of interest that could arise because <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION> gets federal funds for its programs. In fiscal 1988, the school received $ 5.8 million from HHS. Federal ethics officials indicated last week that <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> would be able to receive payments from the school while serving at <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, deputy director of the Office of Government Ethics, said ethics officials had met with <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> and his lawyers and `` all the problems have been worked out.'' A government source familiar with <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s situation said the nominee had a specific written contract entitling him to certain payments for a leave of absence, based on days of service. <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION>, like many academic institutions, gives its faculty paid sabbatical leaves based on years of service. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> was allowed a paid sabbatical after 13 years of uninterupted service, the White House said. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, in Saturday's editions, quoted a friend of <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s as saying the nominee had accrued about $ 300,000 worth of sabbatical leave. But <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said in his statement, `` President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has called on all of those in his Cabinet ... to set the very highest ethical standards, and to avoid even the appearance of potential conflicts of interest. I agree emphatically with the president.'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s decision resolves one of the issues that has held up his confirmation hearings in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> last week postponed <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s confirmation hearings indefinitely at the request of the White House The panel is awaiting completion of an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> background check that is focusing in part on <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s ties to <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Eaves </PERSON>, a suspended <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, commissioner who has been convicted of extortion. In a matter unrelated to the extortion case, Eaves was paid more than $ 34,000 over four years as a lecturer at <LOCATION> Morehouse </LOCATION> while using his seat