<HEAD>Cold And Drought Threaten Swans, Wind Stymies Bighorn Relocation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cold Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly a quarter of the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> population of trumpeter swans is in danger of starvation at their winter feeding grounds in eastern <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials say. Service biologist <PERSON> Signe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sather-Blair </PERSON> blames the 1988 drought and current arctic cold for preventing the birds from getting their normal food. They are not on the endangered species list, but they are on <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s Sensitive Species list. The swans feed on aquatic plants, and low water in <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>'s Fork of the <LOCATION> Snake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> has been frozen over. The roughly 500 birds are unable to break through the ice to reach their food. Elsewhere in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, the cold and accompanying high wind has interfered with state efforts to transplant bighorn sheep by helicopter. In an attempt to rescue the swans, Fish and Wildlife was granted 1,600 acre-feet of water from irrigators in the <LOCATION> Snake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Water </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> and also received $ 8,000 from the Nature Conservancy to purchase an additional 3,200 acre-feet of water. However, wildlife biologist <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Gail </PERSON>, who has studied the swans for the Idaho Fish and Game Department, said Friday that the increased water flow had not broken up the ice on the river. `` There is no way to measure what condition they are in now,'' Ms. <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> said of the swans. `` But it's pretty grim. They've had decreased food supplies for 2 -LCB- months already this winter.'' Ms. <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> said other swans, as many as 800, that water on lakes and rivers around <ORGANIZATIO