<HEAD>After 13 Years, Mafia Commission Releases Files</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The most exhaustive Mafia study ever done by the Italian government was released Saturday, 13 years after it was completed, news reports said. The 3,852-page study lists the names of 2,405 people and 345 organizations or businesses collected by a special parliamentary commission set up in 1962 to probe the Mafia, according to the <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION> news agency and state-run television. The names range from well-known Italian politicians to such fabled Mafiosi as <PERSON> Lucky </PERSON> <PERSON> Luciano </PERSON>, the Italian-American gangster, the <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION> report said. `` The files published today do n't refer to people suspected of belonging to the Mafia or having links with it, but instead to every person ... insinuated ... in a situation of this -LRB- Mafia -RRB- type,'' said the introduction written by Sen. <PERSON> Gerardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiaromonte </PERSON>, according to <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION>. Chiaromonte is head of the current parliamentary anti-Mafia commission. Sources for the names included police, newspaper reports, witnesses who testified before the commission and anonymous tips. The report's release had been expected since Chiaromonte's commission voted in November and again in December to make it public No one answered the telephone in Chiaromonte's office Saturday, and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> press office was closed. It was not clear whether the report would have much effect, both because of its age and the varying credibility of the sources. <PERSON> Chiaromonte </PERSON> said the commission decided to make the list public in order to dispel any suspicion that `` a public organism wants to hide, in all or in part, news regarding the involvement of politicians in Mafia affairs.'' Links between politicians and the Mafia have been a hot topic since the so-called `` maxi-trial'' ended in December 1987 with 338 people found guilty. The 30-member parliamentary commission issued statements listing the names of some suspected Mafia leaders. But the final report did not give names. The part made public called for trying suspected organized crime figures on tax charges and increasing surveillance of them. Leftist members of the commission, in a minority, had charged that `` powder keg'' revelations were being covered up. But other members of the commission said unsubstantiated charges should not be published. The report released Saturday focuses on Mafia activity from 1963 to the early 1970s. It reportedly includes names of local and national politicians ranging from communists to members of the far-right <ORGANIZATION> Italian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>. Among those denounced to the commission were several politicians, judges and writers who had taken strong stands against the <ORGANIZATION> Mafia </ORGANIZATION>, suggesting that some people tried to use the investigation to damage their enemies. One senator who accused several politicians of having Mafia ties was himself later charged by an anonymous source with having links to the Mafia.
