 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has donated several abandoned buildings to the community before tearing down most of its former car assembly plant here, officials said. The company, whose auto assembly lines in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> were closed in December, announced Friday that some structures would remain for use by the city, county and <ORGANIZATION> Gateway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> executive administrator, said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> wanted to raze all the main plant buildings except for an engine factory and stamping operation, but local officials persuaded it to donate some buildings. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dauch </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president of manufacturing, said the donations represent about 550,000 square feet of office and factory space in four buildings. In addition, some land near a municipal golf course will be deeded to the city of 80,000 residents, he said. The plant's main office building will be donated to <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> for its <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, officials said. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said officials plan to move the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> Job Service into the building to create a central location for former <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers seeking welfare and job-hunting help. <PERSON> Dauch </PERSON> said a factory building will be turned over to <ORGANIZATION> Gateway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> for a business incubator center. A nearby building will be donated for the school's administrative offices. <ORGANIZATION> Kenosha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> will move into a fourth building. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> obtained the factory complex as part of its 1987 purchase of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The complex had been used for automaking for 86 years. Chrysler announced in January 1988 that it would shut down most of the plant, citing its age and inefficiency. <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> officials threatened to sue <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, saying the automaker had promised verbally to keep the plant open through 1992 in exchange for $ 5 million in state job training funds. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> reached an out-of-court settlement that included $ 250 million in aid to workers, the community of nearly 80,000 residents and the state. About 4,500 jobs were lost last year when <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> closed the factory except for engine production. The company's 1.8-million-square-feet engine plant, which employs 1,350 workers, will remain in operation, <PERSON> Dauch </PERSON> said. The company also will retain ownership of several parking lots and a shipping yard, he said.
