<HEAD>Fourth Game In Timman-Portisch Match Adjourned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANTWERP, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The fourth game in the World Chess Championship Candidates quarterfinal between <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Lajos </PERSON> <PERSON> Portisch </PERSON> was adjourned after 62 moves Saturday. The bishops and pawns left on the board after six hours of play might still hide some surprises but experts felt a draw would be the most likely outcome. Dutch grandmaster <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiel </PERSON>, who visited the tournament hall in the basement of an <LOCATION> Antwerp </LOCATION> luxury hotel to see his countryman in action, even said he expected the two opponents would sign the draw without further play. `` Of course, <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> will analyze the position thoroughly with his seconds overnight, but I for one do n't see how he could possibly avoid splitting the point with <LOCATION> Portisch </LOCATION> in this one,'' <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiel </PERSON> said. A draw would be a serious setback for the 37-year-old <PERSON> Timman </PERSON>, who played white in Saturday's game and desperately needed a victory to catch up with his 51-year-old Hungarian opponent. <PERSON> Portisch </PERSON> won the third encounter the day before and was leading 2-1 with only two more games to go in the six-game match, one of a series of knock-out contests to select a challenger who will play world champion <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> for his title in 1990. <PERSON> Timman </PERSON> started the game well, following a line from the <PERSON> Ruy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> to build up a better position and concentrating his forces on the queenside, where he seemed set to launch a strong offensive. At the decisive moment, however, he hesitated, playing a number of careful moves, when he might have pressed his advantage and start an all-out offensive. <PERSON> Portisch </PERSON> reacted immediately, exchanging queens and, after some tactical complications, getting the rooks off the board as well. Even <PERSON> Timman </PERSON>'s West German second, <PERSON> Vlastimil </PERSON> <PERSON> Hort </PERSON>, admitted the Hungarian was `` playing a fine defending game'' at that stage. `` Portisch kept a cool head'', he said. `` Jan's attack seemed decisive, but maybe <PERSON> Portisch </PERSON> had calculated farther and decided he could take the risk.'' `` Jan was probably right in not going all out. In fact, I think it's a miracle the way he is playing, especially after the defeat he suffered yesterday. Most players would not even try. They would settle for a draw the day after they lost a game,'' <PERSON> Hort </PERSON> said. Public attention for the duel was overwhelming at first, with about one hundred spectators watching in the silence of the tournament hall, while another two hundred thronged the auditorium next door, where two Belgian masters, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Meulders </PERSON> and <PERSON> Luc </PERSON> <PERSON> Winants </PERSON>, were commenting on the game _ Meulders in Flemish and <PERSON> Winants </PERSON> in French. But after <PERSON> Portisch </PERSON> had succeeded in maintaining the balance and the game developed into an ever more drawish position, most people went home until only a handful were left to see <PERSON> Portisch </PERSON> seal his move at the 62nd. The resumption is to be played on Sunday with the fifth game following on Monday.
