ION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> regulators. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> said top officials of the failed <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marino </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> were told they could avoid prosecution by helping regulators recover some of the money lost when the thrift institution collapsed in 1984. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said the offer was a misunderstanding made without consultation with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and that bank board regulators have been warned not to do it again. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> also met with the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> group that assesses judicial appointees and said he thinks it will continue to play a role in evaluating <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration nominees to the federal bench. In his remarks to the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> luncheon, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration will be a tough fighter against street crime. `` Firm and effective action against drug-related criminal activities, including application of the newly enacted federal death penalty, will be necessary to end the free-fire zones that have taken the lives of so many innocent people,'' he said. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> also said he supports a pay raise of about 50 percent for federal judges that is due to take effect unless both houses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> vote to block it before Wednesday. `` It's absolutely essential that the pay-raise bill take effect,'' he said. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> also said he will press for higher pay for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys and <ORGANIZATION> FB