ition of anonymity, estimated fatalities at 300. Soldiers raided the house of <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s justice minister, <PERSON> Eugenio </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacquet </PERSON>, carting away boxes of documents, the radio reported. It said <PERSON> Jacquet </PERSON> was en route home from <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, where he represented <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> at the inauguration Thursday of President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. The former interior minister and leder of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Sabino </PERSON> <PERSON> Montanaro </PERSON>, was reportedly given shelter at the <ORGANIZATION> Honduran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. New details emerged about the coup. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> is the biggest and best-equipped in the 12,500-man army, apparently tried to arrest <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> on Thursday as he dined at the home of a friend near the corps' base. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s bodyguards resisted and he escaped to the escort battalion, according to a witness who saw the exchange of gunfire. The witness said that after a battle at the barracks, he saw <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> being driven off in his black Chevrolet between two tanks. Opposition groups said they hoped the transition boded new opportunity for them. `` I consider the overthrow of that tyrant as the most positive event in our country's political history over the last 40 years,'' said <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrada </PERSON> <PERSON> Nogues </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> had refused to