<HEAD>Yusupov Defeats Spraggett In Sudden Death Playoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUEBEC (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Artur </PERSON> <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> scored a brilliant victory over <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Spraggett </PERSON> in a sudden-death playoff Saturday to win their World Chess Championship Candidates quarterfinal and advance to the semifinal stage. With both players' thinking time limited to one hour each for the entire game, <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON>, playing black, unleashed a dazzling queen sacrifice on his 28th move to gain a crushing attack with his remaining pieces against <PERSON> Spraggett </PERSON>'s King. `` It was the best move in all the match.'' said <PERSON> Yves </PERSON> <PERSON> Boisvert </PERSON>, a Canadian chess commentator. As <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON> steadied his nerves and waited to deliver an unstoppable checkmate on his 51st move, <PERSON> Spraggett </PERSON> ran out of time and lost the game. `` I'm not disappointed. I lost, but I think I gave it my best,'' <PERSON> Spraggett </PERSON> told reporters at a joint news conference with his opponent onstage at the playing hall in <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>'s Gabrielle-Roy Library. <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON> said <PERSON> Spraggett </PERSON> had proved his equal by holding him to a 4-4 tie over the eight games played before Saturday at a slower rate. After his victory, <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON> rushed from the hall to tell his wife, <PERSON> Tatiana </PERSON>, of the victory. Following <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost, wives of Soviet Grandasters have, in the last months, begun to travel to the west with their husbands. When the players came back to the stage, they received a standing ovation of more than a minute from the disappointed, but appreciative Canadian crowd. The winner of the Candidates, a series of knockout matches, will challenge world champion <PERSON> Garri </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON> for his title in 1990. <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON>, a 28-year-old Muscovite joins British Grandmaster <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> in the semifinals. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Dvoretsky </PERSON>, a Soviet international master who acts as <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON>'s second, said <PERSON> Yusupov </PERSON> would probably play former world champion and fellow Soviet <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> in the semifinals. <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> is currently leading <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Johann </PERSON> <PERSON> Hjartarson </PERSON> 3-1 in the six-game duel underway in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, and requires only one draw from two games to win the contest. <PERSON> Speelman </PERSON> is likely to meet either <PERSON> Lajos </PERSON> <PERSON> Portisch </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> or Dutch Grandmaster <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Timman </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Portisch </LOCATION> is leading their contest in <LOCATION> Antwerp </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> 2-1 after three games. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Finta </PERSON>, the general director of the <ORGANIZATION> Quebec </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> who oragnized the contest with the support of <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>'s provincial government said the players would split the $ 42,000 prize fund becasue the match was tied after the initial six games. Both semifinals will be staged together in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in the autumn. Each contest wil feature a prize $ 125,000, with five-eighths to the winner and three-eighths for the loser. In a remarakable incident at the 1983 Candidates quarterfinal between <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Huebner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and former world champion <PERSON> Vassily </PERSON> <PERSON> Smyslov </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Velden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, organizers turned to the roulettte table to break the tie. <PERSON> Huebner </PERSON> refused to attend, and on the first spin, the ball landed on the zero. But on the second roll, the ball landed on red and gave <PERSON> Smyslov </PERSON> victory. He went on to reach the Candidates final before being knockout out by <PERSON> Kasparov </PERSON>.
