 <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> ASEAN </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- want <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> to head a coalition government to take power after <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s pullout, tentatively set for September. The prince is thought to be the only man with broad enough support to unify his nation, but his unpredictable diplomatic ploys have also complicated efforts to resolve the conflict. He has on several occasions resigned as president of the three-party resistance government because of differences with his coalition partners. Last month he announced he would boycott all further peace talks because <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>, prime minister of the Vietnam-backed government in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>, had rejected his proposals for introducing an international peacekeeping force after <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> ends its 10-year occupation. He has since modified his position, saying he will support any unanimous agreements coming out of talks in <LOCATION> Jakarta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> later this month among the warring factions. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> was ousted in a 1970 coup he alleged was engineered by the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>. However, his faction now receives non-military aid from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which calls for an end to the Vietnamese occupation and the holding of free elections in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>.
