<TEXT>
 Some 3,000 Moslems marched in this central English city Saturday to protest the book `` The Satanic Verses,'' which they consider blasphemous. Demonstrators from around the country marched from Central Mosque to <LOCATION> Chamberlain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> in the city center, where they heard speeches from religious leaders and delivered a protest petition to city hall. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Midlands </LOCATION> police estimated the number of marchers at 3,000 and said the protest was peaceful. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and some <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> nations have banned <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s `` The Satanic Verses,'' which is named after the verses the Prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> removed from the Koran _ the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> holy book _ on grounds they were inspired by the devil. Copies have been burned at protests in the northern city of <LOCATION> Bradford </LOCATION>, which has a large Moslem population, and last week demonstrators marched in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and vowed to take legal action over its publication. Indian-born <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> describes `` The Satanic Verses'' as a moral parable about contemporary <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. It has been a best-seller in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, won the Whitbread Novel Award in 1988 and was runner-up for the prestigious Booker Prize.
