<HEAD>`Biggest Free Party in World' Under Way</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with parades, injury, quote. Picks
up 5th graf, `Some roisterers ...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parade-watchers and party-goers bundled up Saturday against a suddenly cold Carnival weekend, the start of a four-day spectacle expected to draw nearly 2 million merrymakers by <PERSON> Mardi </PERSON> <PERSON> Gras </PERSON>. Nine parades rolled Saturday in metropolitan <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, including the extravagant Endymion with huge floats and celebrity riders such as <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Savage </PERSON>, the child television star of `` The Wonder Years,'' and pop singers <PERSON> Daryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Oates </PERSON>. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> police estimated this will be the biggest <LOCATION> Mardi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gras </LOCATION> ever, with 1.7 million revelers lining the streets and jamming the French Quarter on Fat Tuesday, the last blowout before the solemn season of Lent. Authorities said 1.5 million people attended the 1988 celebration. Police reported few problems during the parades Saturday, which drew thousands of revelers. The lone injury was a float rider who required stitches after she was hit in the head by an undetermined object during an all-women's parade. The day was cloudy, cold and damp, with temperatures in the 40s and chilling winds. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said an arctic air mass would drop temperatures into the 30s through Tuesday, but that did n't deter Saturday night's parade-stalkers. `` The crowd is really just as big as normal. As long as it does n't rain, they'll come out,'' said <PERSON> Hilda </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON>, desk clerk at the Hummingbird Hotel, along the Endymion route. Some roisterers sought internal and external warmth in bars along oak-lined <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>, a major parade route. `` They're here anyway and they're going to go drinking,'' said <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendricks </PERSON> at Fat Harry's. `` Instead of standing outside, it just gets packed inside. The cold weather makes no difference.'' For others visitors, there were worse things to deal with than the damp, winter weather _ the city's notorious hard-line parking regulations and always-ready tow trucks. `` I thought my car was stolen,'' said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, whose rental car was town away before a parade earlier this week. `` But after they checked the license, they told me, ` We have it.' I could n't believe it,'' he said. The New Orleans Streets Department begins towing two hours before parade time. Signs in Carnival colors of purple, green and gold alert drivers to the financial hazards of blocking parade routes. For some <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> students, the problem was n't cars, it was hotel space. When 10 buses from <LOCATION> Gainesville </LOCATION> pulled up to the Days Inn in suburban <PERSON> Kenner </PERSON> on Friday, nearly 200 of the 600 students learned they did n't have a place to sleep. `` We had all made our commitments to come here _ paid the travel agency for everything in full,'' said student <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON>. `` But somewhere along the way, somebody screwed up.'' Five hours later, Days Inn Manager <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Gator </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> owners <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahlen </PERSON> found 15 rooms to handle 60 students, while the rest were put in rooms that already held two students each.
