<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-abortion protests Saturday in south <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> resulted in more than 130 arrests, police said. In <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, 107 people who blocked the entrance to the Women's Clinic were arrested, but the demonstrators were freed within hours on their own recognizance, an organizer said. Demonstrators were carried off by police, charged with trespassing and unlawful assembly and booked at the <LOCATION> Broward </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jail </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Katie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <LOCATION> Rescue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the rally organizer. Police said about 100 arrests were made but could not give a specific number. No violence was reported. The Women's Clinic closed for a few hours during the demonstration. In <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, police said they arrested more than two dozen people who attempted to block the entrance to the parking lot at the Reproductive Health Services clinic. They declined to disclose the exact number of arrests. The protesters laid down in a driveway to block cars attempting to get into the lot, but police picked them up and put them into a van. About 30 officers formed a shield around the front door of the clinic, keeping the protesters away from the entrance. Several hundred pro-choice demonstrators marched past the health center during the protest, but there was no confrontation. The protest came on the final day of a three-day event that the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pro-Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Direct </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> called `` Rescue St. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON>.'' Thirty-eight protesters