<HEAD>Separate Fires Kill Four In Grand Rapids Suburb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENTWOOD, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two separate fires believed to have both started in chimneys killed four people and critically injured a fifth person early Saturday in this Grand Rapids suburb, authorities said. The fires broke out within a 2 -LCB- - hour period in homes of nearly identical construction located about two miles apart, Fire Chief <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> said Both apparently began in chimneys, he said. `` The layout of the houses are identical. The interiors were built the same; the stairways in the same way; the victims were found in the same location of -LRB- each -RRB- house,'' <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> said. `` There were a lot of coincidences.'' The first blaze killed <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>, 32; her 3-year-old son, <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON>, and 13-month-old daughter, <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON>, officials said. The woman's husband, <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON>, was not home at the time. The victim of the second fire was identified as <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Berggren </PERSON>, 35. Her husband, <PERSON> David </PERSON>, 49, rescued their two young daughters before being admitted to <ORGANIZATION> Blodgett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in Grand Rapids, where he was listed in critical condition Saturday night with burns over 70 percent of his body.
