<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was using his Camp David mountain hideaway today to work on a plan for solving the savings and loan crisis that aides said was unlikely to embrace a controversial deposit insurance fee. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was meeting at the <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> compound with <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, Budget Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> and other key advisers to go over the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s recommendations for S & amp; Ls. White House aides, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they did not expect the president to reach a final decision on the complete S & amp; L package, although a depositors' fee seems to have been ruled out. Administration officials have refused to disavow the fee publicly, but aides conceded privately that the plan most likely would not include it.
